    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Ibuprofen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) that works by inhibiting the activity of the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes. These enzymes are responsible for converting arachidonic acid into prostaglandins and thromboxanes, which are lipid compounds that play a key role in inflammation and pain signaling.\n\nCOX-1 is constitutively expressed in most tissues and is involved in the production of prostaglandins that protect the stomach lining and regulate blood clotting. COX-2, on the other hand, is induced during inflammation and is responsible for producing prostaglandins that mediate pain, fever, and inflammation.\n\nIbuprofen is a non-selective inhibitor of both COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes, meaning it can inhibit the production of both types of prostaglandins. By blocking the activity of these enzymes, ibuprofen reduces the production of prostaglandins, leading to decreased inflammation and pain. However, because it also inhibits COX-1, it can have side effects such as gastrointestinal irritation and increased risk of bleeding.\n\nI hope this explanation helps with your exam. Let me know if you have any further questions.",
